WEBVTT

00:01.482 --> 00:03.206
[Bill chuckling]

00:03.275 --> 00:06.620
♪♪

00:06.724 --> 00:08.103
What's all this?

00:08.172 --> 00:09.655
Daddy just taught me

00:09.827 --> 00:11.379
how to change my spark plugs
and change my oil.

00:11.482 --> 00:13.379
She learned almost as fast
as Bruce did.

00:13.482 --> 00:15.206
So, Dad's teaching you
to work on cars?

00:15.310 --> 00:16.655
Well,
he didn't want to at first.

00:16.724 --> 00:19.034
Said being oily and greasy
was "unladylike."

00:19.137 --> 00:22.172
But saving $2.50 on a tune-up
is beautiful.

00:22.241 --> 00:23.689
Mm-hmm.
[chuckles]

00:23.862 --> 00:25.896
Dean, tell your mother
to grab the Instamatic

00:26.000 --> 00:27.413
and take a picture.

00:27.517 --> 00:28.896
-[laughs]
-Ooh.

00:29.000 --> 00:31.931
[Joe Cocker's
"Feelin' All right" plays]

00:32.034 --> 00:36.206
♪♪

00:36.275 --> 00:40.551
♪♪

00:40.620 --> 00:44.586
♪ Seems I've got to have
a change of scene♪

00:44.655 --> 00:47.413
ADULT DEAN: It's not easy being
the youngest of three children.

00:47.482 --> 00:48.793
The firstborn

00:48.896 --> 00:49.827
gets your parents'

00:49.931 --> 00:51.551
undivided attention.

00:51.655 --> 00:55.965
♪ Imprisoned by the way
it could have been♪

00:56.034 --> 00:58.275
ADULT DEAN: The second-born
gets a little less attention,

00:58.344 --> 00:59.448
but they're still
getting that shine.

00:59.517 --> 01:01.482
♪ So it seems♪

01:01.551 --> 01:03.034
ADULT DEAN: And then you get
to the third child.

01:03.137 --> 01:04.965
You're lucky
if you can get them

01:05.034 --> 01:07.172
to point that camera
in your direction.

01:07.241 --> 01:09.068
♪ But someone locked the door
and took the key♪

01:09.172 --> 01:12.344
ADULT DEAN:
I'm not even sure that's me.

01:12.413 --> 01:13.620
♪ You feelin' all right?♪

01:13.724 --> 01:15.758
ADULT DEAN:
Even though I was the youngest,

01:15.827 --> 01:18.310
I was not gonna be denied
the cool bonding experiences

01:18.413 --> 01:20.724
my brother and sister
got to have with our family.

01:20.793 --> 01:23.310
Dad, I want to go hunting
with you and Granddaddy Clisby.

01:23.413 --> 01:26.206
Now, where'd you come up
with a crazy idea like that?

01:29.758 --> 01:31.517
You know those rabbits
aren't asleep, right?

01:31.620 --> 01:33.620
[clears throat]

01:33.689 --> 01:36.310
I mean, wouldn't a movie
be just as fun?

01:36.379 --> 01:38.034
I can look up
some matinee times right now.

01:38.137 --> 01:39.620
But when
Bruce went hunting,

01:39.689 --> 01:41.551
it was
all the Williams men together.

01:41.655 --> 01:43.896
I just want to do
the same things he did.

01:44.000 --> 01:47.482
It seems [sighs]
important or something.

01:47.551 --> 01:49.448
Plus, I got my new camera

01:49.551 --> 01:51.379
-ready to capture it all.
-[camera clicks]

01:51.448 --> 01:53.000
I'll, uh,
think about it.

01:53.068 --> 01:54.896
You know
that's a no, right?

01:55.000 --> 01:56.655
Fine.
If you won't take me,

01:56.758 --> 01:59.206
I'll just have to go ask
Granddaddy Clisby.

01:59.275 --> 02:01.413
Bill Williams, you know there's
no way on God's green Earth

02:01.413 --> 02:02.931
I'm letting my son
go into the woods

02:03.000 --> 02:05.068
with a nearsighted old man
holding a shotgun.

02:05.137 --> 02:07.344
So, I guess
that's a yes.

02:07.448 --> 02:08.655
[chuckles softly]

02:10.241 --> 02:12.931
[Bill sighs]

02:13.000 --> 02:15.448
-[car door closes]
-We're stopping again?

02:15.517 --> 02:17.034
♪♪

02:17.137 --> 02:19.310
I'll take a pee break
every 15 minutes if I want to.

02:19.379 --> 02:20.551
It's one of the perks
of getting old,

02:20.655 --> 02:22.689
and you can't
take that from me.

02:23.827 --> 02:27.482
So, how many rabbits
did Bruce kill his first time?

02:27.551 --> 02:29.827
-I have no living memory --
-Because I'm gonna double it,

02:29.896 --> 02:32.586
maybe even triple it.

02:32.689 --> 02:34.896
What's with
the scratching?

02:35.000 --> 02:36.689
Must be mosquitoes.

02:36.758 --> 02:38.103
From the car?

02:38.206 --> 02:39.793
Eh, false alarm.

02:39.896 --> 02:42.724
The boy's complaining
about bugs already?

02:42.793 --> 02:44.275
We're not even
in the woods yet.

02:44.379 --> 02:45.482
He needs
to toughen up.

02:45.586 --> 02:48.068
Not bugs, Dad,
chicken pox.

02:48.137 --> 02:49.724
Ohh.

02:49.793 --> 02:52.965
"Oh" what?
"Oh" what, Dean?

02:53.068 --> 02:54.344
A bunch of kids
got the chicken pox

02:54.448 --> 02:55.655
at my school
this week.

02:55.724 --> 02:57.379
And I'm just
hearing about this now?

02:57.551 --> 02:59.689
After spending three hours
cooped up with you in the car?

02:59.689 --> 03:01.137
I want
to yell at you,

03:01.206 --> 03:05.172
but I got to take
another pee break...again.

03:05.275 --> 03:10.413
♪♪

03:10.517 --> 03:13.586
Yep.
It's definitely chicken pox.

03:16.241 --> 03:18.413
ADULT DEAN: I'd never seen
my mom move that fast.

03:18.517 --> 03:20.896
She was avoiding me like
the plague -- literally.

03:20.965 --> 03:23.241
W-What's wrong?
Y-You're scaring me.

03:23.310 --> 03:25.551
Oh, baby, it's nothing
to be worried about.

03:25.620 --> 03:26.896
I just haven't had
the chicken pox,

03:26.965 --> 03:28.724
and you're
very contagious.

03:28.827 --> 03:30.034
And you two.

03:30.137 --> 03:33.000
You are gonna have to hole up
in this house separately. Kim?

03:33.103 --> 03:34.758
Ew. What is with
all this noise?

03:34.793 --> 03:36.241
I can't
hear myself think.

03:36.310 --> 03:38.344
Stop. Don't move.
Dean has chicken pox.

03:38.448 --> 03:39.931
Oh, you are not
getting me sick.

03:40.000 --> 03:41.931
-I just got over mono.
-Mono?

03:42.000 --> 03:43.551
You said it was
a lingering cold.

03:43.655 --> 03:46.034
We need to be worried
about Dean right now.

03:46.137 --> 03:47.517
Well, just go pack
your bags.

03:47.586 --> 03:49.206
You and I are staying
at Grandma's.

03:49.310 --> 03:51.551
-Don't got to tell me twice.
-Wait.

03:51.655 --> 03:54.000
So it's gonna be me,
Granddaddy Clisby, and Dad

03:54.068 --> 03:56.379
in the same house alone
for a week?

03:56.448 --> 03:57.758
You can't just abandon me
with them, Lil.

03:57.862 --> 03:59.793
Wha-- And where do you think
you're going?

03:59.896 --> 04:02.620
I'm, uh, I'm heading home.
It's dinner time.

04:02.724 --> 04:05.586
-It's 4:30, Granddad.
-Damn. It's gonna be cold.

04:05.655 --> 04:08.103
Clisby, have you
had chicken pox before?

04:08.206 --> 04:09.862
I've had everything
from the Spanish flu,

04:09.931 --> 04:11.827
mustard gas,
hoof-and-mouth.

04:11.931 --> 04:13.310
You name it,
I'm immune to it.

04:13.413 --> 04:15.000
Dad, you got to
take this seriously.

04:15.103 --> 04:17.137
Chicken pox at your age
can be really dangerous.

04:17.241 --> 04:18.758
Mm-hmm, and I'm not
letting you go home

04:18.827 --> 04:20.000
to infect
Mother Williams.

04:20.103 --> 04:21.517
Lord knows
she's suffered enough.

04:21.620 --> 04:23.965
Fine, fine. But I'm not
gonna be happy about it.

04:24.034 --> 04:26.551
-Dinner's on the stove.
-But it's just boiling water.

04:26.655 --> 04:29.137
Oh, you'll have to
finish it yourselves.

04:29.206 --> 04:31.241
Love you, baby.
Take care. Bye.

04:31.344 --> 04:32.896
ADULT DEAN:
Maybe I was gonna get

04:33.000 --> 04:34.862
that bonding experience
after all.

04:34.965 --> 04:37.517
Well,
I take dinner at 5:00,

04:37.586 --> 04:39.103
and, uh,
after that,

04:39.206 --> 04:41.827
one of you gonna have to
run my bath water.

04:44.551 --> 04:47.413
You're sleeping outside.

04:47.482 --> 04:49.379
♪ All I know♪

04:49.448 --> 04:53.137
♪ Ohhh, through
the highs and the lows♪

04:53.241 --> 04:57.206
♪ I'mma find my way home♪

04:58.103 --> 05:01.965
♪♪

05:02.034 --> 05:04.000
I'm not
gonna sugarcoat this.

05:04.103 --> 05:06.034
It's gonna be hard,
real hard.

05:06.137 --> 05:07.344
Are you kidding me?

05:07.448 --> 05:09.034
This is gonna be
so great!

05:09.137 --> 05:11.551
We can finally hang out
like we planned --

05:11.655 --> 05:14.896
maybe play some cards,
swap some stories.

05:15.000 --> 05:18.344
Just three generations
of us Williams men.

05:18.413 --> 05:20.034
It's gonna be
two generations

05:20.103 --> 05:21.413
if you
don't stop yapping.

05:21.517 --> 05:23.068
How about
you don't threaten my son?

05:23.172 --> 05:24.724
I was talking
about myself.

05:24.793 --> 05:26.379
First off,
we're gonna have to

05:26.448 --> 05:28.034
divvy up
the household duties.

05:28.103 --> 05:30.448
Well, since you were a cook
in the Army,

05:30.551 --> 05:32.724
it's only right
that you cook for us.

05:32.793 --> 05:34.931
Wow. Thanks for
the vote of confidence.

05:35.000 --> 05:37.172
Yeah, see,
I was in the infantry,

05:37.172 --> 05:38.586
like a real man.

05:38.655 --> 05:40.137
So I'll be sure
to shoot the first one

05:40.241 --> 05:41.517
who tries
to break in.

05:41.620 --> 05:42.793
Good thinking.

05:42.862 --> 05:44.482
Dean, you do
your regular chores.

05:44.551 --> 05:46.551
And stop scratching.
That's how it spreads.

05:46.655 --> 05:48.758
So, what chores are you
actually gonna do, Dad?

05:48.827 --> 05:50.344
Oh, I don't do chores.
Never did.

05:50.413 --> 05:52.758
See, my mama did them for me
until I was 16,

05:52.862 --> 05:54.896
and then my wife took over
after that.

05:55.000 --> 05:56.758
Guess what, Dad?
It's the '60s.

05:56.862 --> 05:58.758
Men have evolved
since your generation.

05:58.862 --> 06:00.896
We're not helpless
around the house anymore.

06:01.000 --> 06:02.724
ADULT DEAN: Mm-hmm.
This is the same man

06:02.793 --> 06:04.034
who didn't meet
any of his kids

06:04.103 --> 06:06.379
until the day after
they were born.

06:06.448 --> 06:07.896
Well,
I'm old and feeble.

06:07.965 --> 06:10.551
Ain't that what
you're always telling me?

06:10.620 --> 06:13.793
This pox just might
take me down.

06:13.896 --> 06:14.862
BILL: I see.

06:14.931 --> 06:16.344
So now that there's chores
on the table,

06:16.448 --> 06:18.517
-you're taking this seriously.
-Eh.

06:18.620 --> 06:20.137
You're doing the dishes,
Dad.

06:20.241 --> 06:21.862
ADULT DEAN:
It was finally happening.

06:21.965 --> 06:24.310
All of us Williams men
were gonna rough it together.

06:24.379 --> 06:26.344
It was gonna be just like
rabbit hunting,

06:26.448 --> 06:28.482
minus the hunting
and the rabbits.

06:28.586 --> 06:30.655
Dean,
stop scratching.

06:30.724 --> 06:32.034
Your mother's
gonna kill me

06:32.137 --> 06:33.793
if you end up with a face
full of pox scars.

06:33.862 --> 06:35.172
But it's so itchy.

06:35.241 --> 06:37.551
There's only one way
to fix this.

06:37.655 --> 06:41.689
♪♪

06:41.758 --> 06:44.862
♪♪

06:44.931 --> 06:47.275
Ugh!
Darn it.

06:47.379 --> 06:50.103
God did not
take Adam's rib

06:50.206 --> 06:51.965
so he could scrub
a pot.

06:52.068 --> 06:53.448
You'll get used to
doing chores.

06:53.551 --> 06:55.586
Doing them together
could even be fun.

06:55.689 --> 06:57.620
You know
what's really fun?

06:57.724 --> 06:58.931
Making money.

06:59.000 --> 07:00.379
How's about
I give you 50 cents a day

07:00.379 --> 07:02.413
to do my chores?

07:02.482 --> 07:05.344
ADULT DEAN: While I was hoping
all of us roughing it together

07:05.344 --> 07:06.931
would create a lifelong memory,

07:07.000 --> 07:09.137
I couldn't turn down
a solid side hustle.

07:10.689 --> 07:12.172
And don't tell
your father.

07:14.310 --> 07:15.862
Ahh!

07:15.965 --> 07:18.172
[grunts]

07:18.275 --> 07:21.551
♪♪

07:21.655 --> 07:23.827
[sighs]

07:23.896 --> 07:25.344
♪♪

07:25.413 --> 07:27.620
Well, come on, now.
I'm a little rusty.

07:27.724 --> 07:30.310
Well,
if the pox don't kill us,

07:30.413 --> 07:32.103
this chili sure will.

07:32.206 --> 07:34.517
Well, I don't know how else
we're gonna eat, do you?

07:34.586 --> 07:39.586
♪♪

07:39.655 --> 07:41.758
Now, preheat the oven
to 350

07:41.827 --> 07:43.344
and put it in
for 30 minutes.

07:43.448 --> 07:45.793
ADULT DEAN:
This was before N95s, people.

07:45.862 --> 07:49.137
Mom, I really, really,
really missed your cooking.

07:49.206 --> 07:51.275
All right.
Point made, Dean.

07:51.344 --> 07:52.655
Dean, I can see
you've been scratching.

07:52.827 --> 07:53.965
I brought you something
for the itch.

07:54.034 --> 07:55.551
-Y'all need to use it.
-No, ma'am.

07:55.655 --> 07:57.344
I'm not taking
the white man's medicine.

07:57.413 --> 07:59.000
Dad, I know
you don't trust doctors,

07:59.068 --> 08:00.517
but you can't
avoid them forever.

08:00.620 --> 08:01.724
Watch me.

08:01.827 --> 08:03.068
See what I'm putting up with
over here?

08:03.172 --> 08:05.206
Mm-hmm.
Y'all enjoy yourselves.

08:05.275 --> 08:07.689
-I've got my own remedies...
-[door closes]

08:07.758 --> 08:09.620
...much better
than any doctor's.

08:09.724 --> 08:11.517
-You'll see.
-[doorbell rings]

08:14.724 --> 08:15.965
[screams]

08:16.068 --> 08:18.137
[dramatic music plays]

08:18.241 --> 08:19.517
Oh, good.

08:19.586 --> 08:22.551
My goose is here.

08:22.620 --> 08:24.931
[grunts]

08:25.000 --> 08:27.137
♪♪

08:27.241 --> 08:29.000
Where did this
come from?

08:29.103 --> 08:31.034
I called
my goose guy.

08:31.137 --> 08:33.172
Why do you
need a goose?

08:33.275 --> 08:34.862
To make goose grease.

08:34.965 --> 08:36.206
ADULT DEAN:
If Granddaddy Clisby thought

08:36.310 --> 08:37.724
he was making things clearer,

08:37.827 --> 08:39.344
he was wrong.

08:39.517 --> 08:40.862
Can someone tell me
what the heck a pre-wash is?

08:40.862 --> 08:42.241
Dad, no.

08:42.344 --> 08:44.517
Kept you healthy
your whole childhood, son.

08:44.586 --> 08:45.862
More like
it kept me smelling bad

08:45.931 --> 08:48.068
and swatting flies
my whole childhood.

08:48.137 --> 08:49.896
Dad, Granddad's about to
teach me to make goose grease.

08:50.000 --> 08:51.586
You should join us,
then it'll be

08:51.689 --> 08:54.724
the three generations
of Williams men making memories.

08:54.793 --> 08:56.793
I'm not participating
in any of this nonsense.

08:56.793 --> 08:58.413
Pay him no attention.

08:58.482 --> 09:00.965
You're about to learn
the magic of goose grease.

09:01.068 --> 09:03.000
♪♪

09:03.103 --> 09:04.448
[grunts]

09:04.551 --> 09:06.517
CLISBY: Yeah.

09:06.620 --> 09:08.620
-Now, doesn't that feel better?
-[chuckles]

09:08.689 --> 09:11.034
ADULT DEAN: It actually did
help with the itching.

09:11.137 --> 09:12.827
And my skin felt amazing!

09:12.931 --> 09:14.862
Never been so soft and supple.

09:14.965 --> 09:17.000
I can smell y'all
from inside.

09:17.103 --> 09:18.448
Well, that means
it's working.

09:18.517 --> 09:20.344
It does make me
a little nostalgic for home.

09:20.448 --> 09:21.448
CLISBY: Mm-hmm!

09:21.517 --> 09:22.793
[chuckles]

09:23.034 --> 09:25.551
Hey, Dad,
maybe you should put some on.

09:25.655 --> 09:27.896
-Then the three of us could --
-[flies buzz]

09:27.965 --> 09:30.758
Oh, no! Here come the flies!
They bite! They bite!

09:30.862 --> 09:33.000
-BILL: Eyes! Not the eyes!
-Ow!

09:35.103 --> 09:38.586
ADULT DEAN: By day four, we had
all fallen into a routine.

09:38.689 --> 09:44.655
♪♪

09:44.758 --> 09:47.275
[dishes clatter]

09:47.344 --> 09:50.103
-I was reading that.
-I know.

09:50.172 --> 09:51.620
ADULT DEAN:
But Dad and Granddad were still

09:51.689 --> 09:52.931
getting on
each other's nerves,

09:53.000 --> 09:54.965
which meant there was
zero bonding going on.

09:55.034 --> 09:56.172
And stop scratching,
Dad.

09:56.448 --> 09:57.758
Just use the cream
Lillian brought.

09:57.827 --> 09:59.137
I ain't studdin'
them quacks

09:59.206 --> 10:01.000
down there
at the pharmacy.

10:01.068 --> 10:02.655
Goose grease
works just fine.

10:02.724 --> 10:03.827
The only thing
that goose grease is doing

10:04.206 --> 10:05.482
is making my house
smell like a barnyard.

10:05.551 --> 10:07.862
Listen, if you don't want
me here, I'll be happy to leave.

10:07.965 --> 10:09.103
In fact,
I'm tired of you

10:09.206 --> 10:10.551
always trying to tell me
what to do,

10:10.620 --> 10:12.241
trying to
domesticate me.

10:12.344 --> 10:13.931
[doorbell rings]

10:14.034 --> 10:17.448
How many goose guys
ya got?

10:18.586 --> 10:19.620
-DEAN: Hey, Cory!
-BILL: [chuckles]

10:19.724 --> 10:21.965
-Good to see you, Cliff.
-CORY: Sorry, Dean.

10:22.068 --> 10:23.724
Mrs. Fry made me
bring you your homework.

10:23.793 --> 10:25.586
I tried telling her
you were on death's door

10:25.655 --> 10:27.137
and that you wouldn't need
any algebra in heaven,

10:27.241 --> 10:28.620
but she wasn't
buying it.

10:28.689 --> 10:30.482
It's okay.
At least you tried.

10:30.586 --> 10:33.344
ADULT DEAN: I pretended
to be mad, but secretly,

10:33.448 --> 10:36.000
I was missing
that sweet, sweet arithmetic.

10:36.068 --> 10:37.862
When Vivian heard
y'all were doing the cooking,

10:37.965 --> 10:39.206
she sent me over here
with this casserole.

10:39.310 --> 10:40.724
Here,
let me come inside.

10:40.827 --> 10:43.137
Hey, what are you doing?
We're still contagious.

10:43.206 --> 10:45.137
I-It's all good.
Now, Cory can't come in,

10:45.206 --> 10:46.896
but I can 'cause I got the pox
when I was 7.

10:47.000 --> 10:48.275
I'm immune.

10:48.344 --> 10:52.241
[laughs]

10:52.344 --> 10:54.206
Come on, man.

10:54.275 --> 10:56.551
I get to sit
on the good couch?

10:56.620 --> 10:58.103
You must really
be desperate.

10:58.206 --> 10:59.517
BILL: [chuckles]
You hungry?

10:59.586 --> 11:00.896
Thirsty?

11:00.965 --> 11:02.724
Can I pour you
a scotch?

11:02.793 --> 11:04.034
It's 4:00
in the afternoon, Bill.

11:04.103 --> 11:06.655
Boy, boy, you're a sight
for sore eyes.

11:06.758 --> 11:08.758
Uh, I see being
all cooped up in here

11:08.827 --> 11:10.827
hasn't, uh,
affected you guys at all.

11:10.931 --> 11:12.137
So, what'd I miss
at the barbershop, huh?

11:12.241 --> 11:14.172
Did Hal patch up
with Ida?

11:14.275 --> 11:16.103
Oh, you ain't gonna
believe this. Okay.

11:16.172 --> 11:18.206
So, has Keisa
asked about me?

11:18.310 --> 11:19.931
[chuckles]
Yeah, she has been, actually.

11:20.000 --> 11:21.551
She wanted to come over
and visit you,

11:21.655 --> 11:24.379
but her parents think
chicken pox come from the devil.

11:24.482 --> 11:27.034
They said the same thing
about wearing glasses.

11:27.103 --> 11:28.689
So, what's Lester gonna do
with his settlement check?

11:28.758 --> 11:29.758
What you think
he gonna do with it?

11:29.862 --> 11:31.896
Not make Jesus proud,
that's for damn sure.

11:32.000 --> 11:33.620
-[laughter]
-Right there!

11:33.724 --> 11:36.344
And then he gonna
try to tell me

11:36.413 --> 11:38.103
that he got
Eartha Kitt's phone number.

11:38.206 --> 11:39.689
[laughter]

11:39.758 --> 11:42.034
I've been trying to bond
with my dad and granddad

11:42.034 --> 11:43.310
like Bruce did,

11:43.413 --> 11:45.310
but every time
we get close to it,

11:45.413 --> 11:46.620
something gets
in the way.

11:46.724 --> 11:48.896
Hey, man,
what if you gave me a hug?

11:48.965 --> 11:51.000
Then you'll get
chicken pox.

11:51.103 --> 11:53.344
I know! Look, I got
a social studies test on Friday,

11:53.448 --> 11:54.793
and I have not studied
for it.

11:54.793 --> 11:56.137
Plus,
if I time it right,

11:56.241 --> 11:58.482
I could probably
get out of church, too.

11:58.551 --> 12:00.793
Cory Long,
don't you take one more step.

12:00.862 --> 12:02.793
Boy, have you
lost your mind?

12:02.862 --> 12:04.551
Look, now, you know
your mama gonna blame me

12:04.655 --> 12:06.310
if you get sick.
I'm taking you home.

12:06.379 --> 12:08.000
You going?
You just got here.

12:08.068 --> 12:09.310
CLISBY:
Yeah, stick around.

12:09.379 --> 12:11.172
We could get
a card game going.

12:11.241 --> 12:12.655
Now, I know
y'all going delirious

12:12.724 --> 12:14.000
if y'all are inviting me
to take your money.

12:14.068 --> 12:15.551
I'mma see you fellas.

12:15.620 --> 12:17.103
Uh, hey, Dean, give me --
Slap me some skin, man.

12:17.206 --> 12:19.448
CLIFF: No, no.
Get to the car.

12:19.551 --> 12:21.344
Want to know
what'd be a good idea?

12:21.413 --> 12:23.379
If the three of us
play cards together.

12:23.448 --> 12:25.034
You could even
teach me poker.

12:25.103 --> 12:26.931
You don't know
how to play poker?

12:27.103 --> 12:29.379
Well, you ought to know by now.
[stammers] How old are you? 7?

12:29.448 --> 12:30.482
I'm 12.

12:30.586 --> 12:32.000
You're not gonna teach my son
how to gamble.

12:32.103 --> 12:33.275
Besides,
he doesn't have any money.

12:33.344 --> 12:34.724
-Yeah, he does.
-Yeah, I do.

12:35.793 --> 12:37.241
You know what?

12:37.413 --> 12:39.103
If it'll help us pass the time,
let's do it.

12:39.172 --> 12:40.793
Just don't tell
your mother.

12:40.862 --> 12:42.655
ADULT DEAN: This was it.

12:42.827 --> 12:45.862
My last chance to connect
with the men of my family,

12:45.965 --> 12:48.758
and I was not gonna let
anything ruin it.

12:48.862 --> 12:51.758
We broke so many family rules
that night --

12:51.862 --> 12:54.379
playing poker,
not using coasters,

12:54.482 --> 12:56.172
peeing out the back door.

12:56.241 --> 12:57.862
Mom would've killed us.

12:57.931 --> 13:01.172
Pair of kings.
[laughs]

13:01.241 --> 13:03.586
Uh, I-I've got
some eights and some sixes.

13:03.689 --> 13:05.103
That's something,
right?

13:05.206 --> 13:08.034
[laughs]

13:08.103 --> 13:09.241
Boy, that's a full house.

13:09.310 --> 13:11.137
-Oh, this is gonna be good.
-Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

13:11.241 --> 13:12.482
Beginner's luck,
beginner's luck.

13:12.586 --> 13:13.586
Come on, come on, come on.
Play again.

13:13.655 --> 13:15.241
-Deal, deal, deal.
-[sighs]

13:15.310 --> 13:17.586
ADULT DEAN:
Granddaddy Clisby was right.

13:17.655 --> 13:19.689
My luck started to run out
after that.

13:19.793 --> 13:21.344
Poker's all
about bluffing.

13:21.448 --> 13:23.137
Just act like you're Kim
lying about

13:23.206 --> 13:25.517
why she missed curfew,
except better.

13:25.620 --> 13:27.000
Don't worry, kid.

13:27.103 --> 13:28.827
I've been winning
at poker

13:29.000 --> 13:31.413
since I learned to play in
a foxhole during the Great War.

13:31.517 --> 13:33.586
So what was it like
fighting in World War I?

13:33.689 --> 13:35.413
You might be a little young
for those stories.

13:35.517 --> 13:36.689
I'm old enough
to play poker.

13:36.758 --> 13:38.758
Fine. I guess
I can tell you one story.

13:38.862 --> 13:41.000
♪♪

13:41.068 --> 13:43.206
And that's when I shot down
the Red Baron.

13:43.275 --> 13:45.034
No, you didn't.
No, he didn't.

13:45.103 --> 13:46.586
ADULT DEAN:
Once Granddaddy got started,

13:46.689 --> 13:48.068
there was no stopping him.

13:48.137 --> 13:51.793
I heard about trench warfare,
mustard gas poisoning,

13:51.896 --> 13:53.310
and how he single-handedly
saved Paris

13:53.413 --> 13:55.310
while falling in love
with Josephine Baker.

13:55.413 --> 13:57.310
What about one of your
war stories, Dad?

13:57.413 --> 13:58.827
-Aw.
-CLISBY: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

13:58.931 --> 14:00.758
Tell him about the time
that you sliced your finger

14:00.827 --> 14:02.000
while cutting a tomato

14:02.103 --> 14:04.034
during the battle
of ham sandwich.

14:04.137 --> 14:07.551
You see, your brother, Bruce,
and I fought in combat

14:07.655 --> 14:09.517
while your father
was banging pots

14:09.517 --> 14:11.241
in the safety
of the kitchen.

14:11.344 --> 14:13.517
Well, they say an army marches
to battle on its stomach.

14:13.586 --> 14:15.517
Well,
you got that right.

14:15.620 --> 14:17.034
[both laugh]

14:17.137 --> 14:19.241
You feeling okay?

14:19.344 --> 14:21.724
-Need to lay down?
-Uh, n-no, I'm fine.

14:21.827 --> 14:24.689
L-Let's keep playing.

14:24.758 --> 14:26.344
And we were marching
through this town, see,

14:26.413 --> 14:28.448
and I saw this cute
little French girl --

14:28.551 --> 14:30.586
Not appropriate,
Dad.

14:30.689 --> 14:31.655
ADULT DEAN: This was it.

14:31.827 --> 14:34.310
This was the bonding moment
I'd been waiting for.

14:34.413 --> 14:37.931
I was feeling happy,
feeling redeemed, feeling...

14:38.000 --> 14:39.620
very, very hot.

14:39.724 --> 14:41.586
You okay there,
Dean?

14:41.655 --> 14:43.862
Oh,
you are burning up.

14:43.965 --> 14:45.620
We need
to get you to a doctor.

14:45.689 --> 14:47.310
No, no, no, no,
we ain't going there.

14:47.379 --> 14:49.310
All right? Y-Y-You can't
trust these doctors.

14:49.379 --> 14:51.275
Well, they tell you
they're gonna take your blood,

14:51.344 --> 14:53.413
then they don't tell you
what they're gonna do with it.

14:53.517 --> 14:54.482
Don't listen to him.

14:54.620 --> 14:56.241
This is just nonsense
he hears at the barbershop.

14:56.344 --> 14:57.862
You remember
your cousin Darnell?

14:57.965 --> 14:59.758
Well, he's being treated
by some doctors

14:59.862 --> 15:02.517
over at Tuskegee
in some special studies,

15:02.586 --> 15:04.034
but I'm telling you,

15:04.103 --> 15:06.413
the man is only
getting worse.

15:06.517 --> 15:07.448
ADULT DEAN:
Yeah, that's the one

15:07.620 --> 15:10.034
the history books
still don't talk about enough.

15:10.103 --> 15:11.793
Well, maybe we should just
call it a night, then.

15:11.896 --> 15:13.655
No, we have to
keep playing!

15:13.758 --> 15:15.206
Why is this so important
to you, Dean?

15:15.275 --> 15:17.758
Because you,
Granddaddy, and Bruce

15:17.827 --> 15:19.586
have all these things
in common.

15:19.689 --> 15:22.448
You go hunting and fishing
and do all these manly things,

15:22.517 --> 15:25.172
and I don't get
to do any of it.

15:25.275 --> 15:28.517
I-I just want to be
a part of the Williams men...

15:28.620 --> 15:29.965
for once.

15:30.034 --> 15:34.034
Dean, that's crazy talk.

15:34.137 --> 15:36.448
You'll always be
a Williams man...

15:38.241 --> 15:39.620
...for better or worse.

15:39.689 --> 15:41.517
So, can we still play?

15:41.620 --> 15:44.586
Uh, it's my turn
to deal.

15:44.689 --> 15:47.103
[missiles whistling]

15:47.206 --> 15:48.482
[explosion]

15:48.551 --> 15:50.482
[all scream]

15:50.586 --> 15:53.689
There goes another pair
of clean undies.

15:53.758 --> 15:55.241
[laughs]

15:55.413 --> 15:58.310
ALL [chanting]:
Dean, Dean, Dean, Dean, Dean,

15:58.413 --> 15:59.896
Dean, Dean, Dean, Dean!

15:59.965 --> 16:02.068
Dean!
Can you hear me?

16:02.137 --> 16:03.758
All right,
you doughboys,

16:03.931 --> 16:05.931
it's time to go over the top
and lick those Germans.

16:06.000 --> 16:08.137
He's delirious
and talking crazy.

16:08.206 --> 16:10.137
We need to go now.

16:10.206 --> 16:11.931
Uh, uh, all right.

16:12.000 --> 16:14.103
[Dean murmuring indistinctly]

16:14.172 --> 16:15.137
Dad!

16:15.206 --> 16:16.379
What?

16:19.689 --> 16:22.517
Oh, God, my baby.

16:22.620 --> 16:24.000
I-I'm okay, Mom.

16:24.068 --> 16:25.551
You're gonna live,
right?

16:25.724 --> 16:27.689
ADULT DEAN:
Kim was being nice to me?

16:27.758 --> 16:30.655
Dang. I must've been
sicker than I thought.

16:31.896 --> 16:34.310
Oh, thank God.
Is he okay?

16:34.413 --> 16:36.379
Dean may have gotten
a blood infection

16:36.448 --> 16:38.068
stemming from
the chicken pox.

16:38.137 --> 16:40.448
I'll need to take a blood sample
to be sure.

16:43.068 --> 16:46.689
Oh, no, no,
I am not getting a shot.

16:46.793 --> 16:48.689
What? Baby, it'll just hurt
for a second.

16:48.793 --> 16:50.310
Don't you know
that they take your blood

16:50.379 --> 16:51.620
and do something secret
with it?

16:51.689 --> 16:53.000
That's right.

16:53.275 --> 16:54.310
That's why they call it
medical practice,

16:54.655 --> 16:55.655
because they're practicing
on you.

16:55.758 --> 16:56.689
-Dad.
-Exactly.

16:56.793 --> 16:58.000
Just g-give me
some goose grease,

16:58.068 --> 16:59.068
and I'll be fine.

16:59.172 --> 17:01.482
Wha--
Goose grease?

17:02.482 --> 17:04.103
Dad.

17:07.344 --> 17:09.068
You need to stop.

17:09.137 --> 17:11.172
You're the one who put
this foolishness in his head,

17:11.241 --> 17:15.379
so...you're the one
who needs to get it out.

17:18.103 --> 17:19.896
Okay.

17:19.965 --> 17:21.103
Okay.

17:24.517 --> 17:25.758
So, maybe you ought to

17:25.827 --> 17:28.310
listen to the doctor
just this once.

17:28.413 --> 17:30.517
But you wouldn't let them
take your blood, Granddad.

17:30.620 --> 17:31.827
You told me.

17:31.931 --> 17:34.793
♪♪

17:34.862 --> 17:37.931
Maybe if
we do this together.

17:38.000 --> 17:39.862
You'd do it?

17:41.034 --> 17:43.965
Only if
you do it with me.

17:44.034 --> 17:46.517
Uh, okay.

17:46.620 --> 17:48.172
LILLIAN:
You know what?

17:48.241 --> 17:50.275
Bill hasn't seen a doctor
in years.

17:50.379 --> 17:52.034
Maybe you should
do it, too.

17:52.103 --> 17:58.241
Uh, sure, I'll --
I'll get my blood drawn...

17:58.310 --> 18:00.344
from my body.

18:00.413 --> 18:01.793
You, too, Daddy?

18:01.896 --> 18:03.310
Now, who wants
to go first?

18:03.413 --> 18:04.758
Now, now, now,
if it's --

18:04.827 --> 18:06.965
i-if it's about me,
um,

18:07.068 --> 18:10.172
I want a Black doctor,
but no offense.

18:10.275 --> 18:11.517
Please.
Offense intended.

18:11.620 --> 18:14.034
-Mm-hmm.
-[scoffs]

18:14.137 --> 18:19.310
♪♪

18:19.379 --> 18:21.137
Are you sure you went
to medical school?

18:21.206 --> 18:24.172
Well, w-w-was it
a women's medical school?

18:24.241 --> 18:27.551
Were men
there at that school?

18:27.655 --> 18:28.724
ADULT DEAN:
This wasn't exactly

18:28.827 --> 18:30.413
the bonding experience
I'd wanted

18:30.517 --> 18:32.862
when we set off
on our hunting trip last week,

18:32.931 --> 18:35.344
but seeing the sacrifices
my family made for me,

18:35.413 --> 18:38.137
I felt a new closeness
I hadn't anticipated.

18:38.241 --> 18:40.413
We were like
blood brothers now.

18:40.482 --> 18:42.448
Is your husband
okay with you being a doctor?

18:42.551 --> 18:44.620
[scoffs]
What husband?

18:44.724 --> 18:46.103
I'll let you know
when I meet him.

18:48.413 --> 18:49.482
You see?

18:49.586 --> 18:51.310
That's what happens
when you get an education.

18:51.413 --> 18:53.896
[clicks tongue]

18:54.000 --> 18:56.965
ADULT DEAN: I had set out
to create a bonding experience

18:57.034 --> 18:59.344
with the men of my family,
and it quickly became

18:59.448 --> 19:02.344
a disastrous week
of chicken pox, goose grease,

19:02.413 --> 19:03.620
and bloodletting.

19:03.689 --> 19:05.206
But what I didn't realize

19:05.310 --> 19:07.896
was that you can't force
these kinds of things --

19:08.000 --> 19:09.965
you just got to let them happen
on their own.

19:10.034 --> 19:12.758
Turns out
the moments you don't plan for

19:12.862 --> 19:15.586
are the ones
that make the best memories.

19:15.689 --> 19:18.379
When we got
the blood-test results back,

19:18.448 --> 19:20.310
it turned out
I had a minor infection

19:20.413 --> 19:22.310
that cleared up
after some antibiotics.

19:22.413 --> 19:24.586
Well, glad to see
you got your appetite back.

19:24.689 --> 19:25.620
-Mm-hmm.
-Must mean

19:25.724 --> 19:26.758
you're feeling better.

19:26.827 --> 19:29.310
Yep. Maybe I can even
go to school tomorrow.

19:29.344 --> 19:30.793
Well,
the doctor said

19:30.862 --> 19:33.413
she'd call tonight
to give the all clear.

19:33.482 --> 19:35.551
"She."
Just doesn't sound right.

19:35.655 --> 19:37.551
[stammers]
I'm just glad

19:37.655 --> 19:39.448
that you are back
in the kitchen.

19:39.517 --> 19:43.448
Oh, Clisby, the only reason
I cook delicious food

19:43.517 --> 19:45.344
is to keep
that mouth of yours

19:45.413 --> 19:46.689
occupied and shut.

19:46.793 --> 19:48.310
[chuckles]
You see?

19:48.379 --> 19:50.172
That's what happens
when you get an education.

19:50.241 --> 19:52.206
ADULT DEAN:
Granddaddy surprised everybody

19:52.275 --> 19:53.517
with his perfect blood test,

19:53.586 --> 19:56.551
proving that he's inexplicably
as healthy as a horse.

19:56.655 --> 19:58.000
My dad, on the other hand,

19:58.206 --> 19:59.931
found out he has
high cholesterol.

20:00.034 --> 20:01.620
Come on, Lil.

20:01.793 --> 20:03.413
Why don't you give me
a little piece of that roast?

20:03.482 --> 20:05.241
Bill, you had two eggs
this morning.

20:05.310 --> 20:07.310
You're already over your limit
for the day.

20:07.413 --> 20:09.275
Come on, it's just 'til
you get your numbers down.

20:09.344 --> 20:12.344
Mmm! This pot roast
is delicious.

20:12.448 --> 20:14.758
Well, maybe you could
trade one bite

20:14.827 --> 20:16.689
for one egg
next week.

20:16.793 --> 20:18.172
[laughter]

20:18.275 --> 20:20.000
So this is how
it's gonna be?

20:20.103 --> 20:21.034
[telephone rings]

20:21.137 --> 20:23.137
That must be
the doctor calling.

20:23.206 --> 20:25.517
-What's cholesterol?
-Oh, baby.

20:25.586 --> 20:26.965
LILLIAN: Doctor just told him
he can't have any meat...

20:27.034 --> 20:28.034
-Hello?
-LILLIAN: ...so I need to

20:28.137 --> 20:29.793
cut back on the bacon.

20:29.862 --> 20:31.965
What?

20:32.034 --> 20:34.344
What?
What's wrong?

20:34.413 --> 20:35.586
Is Dean okay?

20:35.689 --> 20:37.482
It's about Bruce.

20:41.241 --> 20:43.379
Thank you.

20:45.758 --> 20:48.310
Uh...

20:48.413 --> 20:50.000
Bruce was injured
in Vietnam.

20:50.103 --> 20:55.172
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh♪

20:55.275 --> 20:56.482
He's alive,
but h-he had --

20:56.586 --> 20:58.172
he had to
get surgery.

20:58.344 --> 21:00.655
They're flying him back
to the V.A. hospital tomorrow.

21:00.758 --> 21:02.172
♪ Ooh-ooh♪

21:02.275 --> 21:04.517
[whimpers]

21:04.620 --> 21:06.310
It's okay.

21:06.413 --> 21:07.965
[Lillian cries]

21:08.034 --> 21:09.896
It's gonna be okay.

21:10.000 --> 21:16.000
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh♪

21:23.620 --> 21:27.379
-- Captioned by VITAC --
